tweet: @gjuneja1 Exactly. It's hard to take early-stage bets when you have a large portfolio. So in order to keep growing, you have to make bigger late-stage bets.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: @real_pavan Depends on when you got in, but it's still in the growth stage, imho.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: The reason I find early stage investing less stressful is that if you size your bet accordingly, and it fails, it probably won't hurt your capital base, and if things are taking off, then you're letting profits compound, on a low-cost basis, if things go to zero. (4/4)

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: The ability to reduce position size due to better liquidity in late-stage is a bug, not a feature.  With early-stage investments, you get to place a small bet, and let it ride as long as you want, mostly as a result of low liquidity. This is when compound growth kicks in. (3/4)

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: When that bet works and the returns exceed projections, you start thinking about de-risking and reducing the position size because your capital investment is usually much larger than an early-stage bet. This significantly affects the reduces the impact of compounded growth. (2/4)

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: I find late-stage investing is a lot more stressful than early-stage. With late, you're typically risking a sizeably larger bet than with early, for a lower return profile.  This can create some interesting scenarios. (1/4)

I'm going to posit that the US is entering a period of "Growthflation".

2-4% economic growth/year, coupled with midrange inflation (4-7%) for the next 3-7 years.  

This starkly contrasts with the "Stagflation" period of the 1970s, where growth was stagnant with high inflation.

tweet: @civickey stopped creating multisig ETH wallets for users last year, due to gas fees >$500 at one stage. These costs are not practical for companies, let alone individual users not earning dollars. (4/7)

tweet: I do want to apologize to anyone who found the tweet offensive, but I've always been an advocate for low-cost blockchains and I will continue to do so because I want to see this technology hit the mainstream. Ethereum will have its place and maybe L2 will help. (3/7)

tweet: Ethereum has been the pioneer in NFT‚Äôs and there may be some long term nostalgic value in owning pieces like cryptopunks, but as NFT‚Äôs go mainstream there is little argument for a high cost and slow network for creators.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: However as competitors to marketplaces emerge, and marketplaces themselves support multiple blockchains, the value of paying a higher price on one blockchain vs another diminishes substantially. Then it becomes a selection of optimizing for cost & speed for minting and transfers.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: In the end, it‚Äôs really about the liquidity pools that form around certain objects and the Blockchains they are minted on. In a world where the leading marketplace, @OpenSea only supports Ethereum, and remains the dominant player - the rationale makes sense.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: An NFT is a digital object with a cryptographically verifiable signature and timestamp and so why would you pay $50+ in fees to mint one on one blockchain, when you do exactly the same thing on another blockchain at a fraction of the cost.

tweet: It's all good and well for Bitcoin maximalists to regurgitate old and outdated narratives to newbies, but thinking for yourself is paramount, especially as market conditions change.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: Arbitrage bots tend to trade back and forth to accumulate BTC, especially during high volatility periods, but if Bitcoin decouples from the crypto market as a trading pair, this won't work long term.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: People are not buying Ethereum, Doge, Solana, or Filecoin to accumulate more BTC. They are doing it because they fundamentally believe in the independent future of those ecosystems or they need those assets for staking, etc. They are not dependent on #Bitcoin to succeed.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet:
Crypto narratives are constantly changing and evolving.

One of the most outdated ones told is that people buying alts are doing it just to accumulate more #Bitcoin. If you were in crypto during 2013-2017 cycles, yes that was true to a large extent, but it is no longer the case.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: 5/5 But, why only now? Covid has created a vacuum for human engagement and instead of engaging in person with family, friends, colleagues and celebrities - so we are forced to go digital in order to fill the void we have for human connection again...

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: 4/5 It‚Äôs clear that people want engagement to be a part of the content creation process, and it‚Äôs happening in real-time. If you look at platforms like Cameo & Onlyfans, engaging real-time with influencers in particular is a valuable and in-demand service offering.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: 3/5 Contrast that with real-time social networks, where the engagement IS the content. It‚Äôs a paradigm shift in how we view social networks. This emerging evolution had an awakening moment when @elonmusk went on Clubhouse earlier this week.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: 2/5 Real-time engagement is not novel (chat rooms have been around for decades), but we can now expect the format to evolve from text, to live audio and video. Facebook, Twitter & Instagram largely focus on static content, where the engagement happens after the content is posted.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: 1/5 The next wave of social networks are going to be Real-Time. @joinClubhouse is a great example of that. Asynchronous networks are ones where the content persists, but the engagement occurs after the fact.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: This sub-$12k consolidation is setting #Bitcoin up for a strong run and if it breaks through, $12k is likely to hold. $20k will be very strong resistance - it may take months to break through the ATH, and volatility will therefore be high in the $12k-$20k range.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: So on the basis that‚Äôs it‚Äôs unlikely that #Bitcoin can ‚Äúonly‚Äù double from here, it‚Äôs either going to $5k or $50k. $20k is not a resting point, as it likely forces an acceleration to $50k. This is not a projection, but instead I‚Äôm just observing the flaw in Sharpe Ratios for BTC.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: A typical Sharpe Ratio with a 50% downside projection (~$5k) and a 200% upside projection ($20k) would produce a Sharpe Ratio of 4. If you do the adjustment to $50k, the adjusted Sharpe Ratio would be 10 - which is an usually great bet!

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: #Bitcoin doesn‚Äôt conform to the typical Sharpe Ratio calculations. For instance, if Bitcoin doubled from here, it‚Äôs likely to go past $50k, which would be a 5x increase from today. This essentially means a 2x increase produces, in effect, a 5x upside.

tweet: I‚Äôve always felt that nominal inflation is healthy, as long as real inflation is low (c. 5%) but central banks seem to want to push inflation down as an argument that it hurts the poor more. Central banks are the bastions of incumbent capital - which goes back to my question.

tweet: I expect that even with another $2trn in USD government stimulus, that it will have little impact on the value of the USD, and not create any inflationary effects on the currency - at least, not in the short term.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: In the same way that Bitcoin has a dominance index in the cryptocurrency markets, the USD has one too.  Right now, even while issuing more dollars, the dominance of the USD is rising, which will offset inflationary effects as global trade is weighted more toward the USD.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: Global money supply is over $70trn, but this includes all currencies. As the US dollar supply increases, it leverages Gresham's law to maintain stability when other countries create stimulus packages that pushes their economies to the brink, devaluing their currencies.

tweet: This is why Italy has a much higher mortality rate - it's hit their aging population very hard and they are still not out the woods yet.  If you have anyone who is older than 50 and that you care about, I highly recommend that you start taking precautions immediately.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: The point of concern and quarantine is to prevent the spread of the virus that could potentially kill millions of people who are 1-2 generations behind us, not to protect the 0-40 year olds who will most likely only suffer from mild symptoms and low mortality rates.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: This blended number looks lowish (1-3%), but if you remove the sub 50 year olds from the denominator, the mortality rate skyrockets. If you think it's ok that your parents or elders die at a potential rate of 15-30% if they catch a highly infectious disease then stop reading now.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: The broken logic thinking that Coronavirus  affects the older population disproportionately and therefore is not as deadly as the flu needs to be stopped.  The current mortality rate is a blended one. This means that we're looking at a mix of young and old people combined.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: As we move into a new decade, I think it is important for us to appreciate that our reality of what is the truth may not be accurate. Keep an open mind and be respectful of people that challenge your most closely held beliefs. You might just learn something...

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: This allows us to invalidate previously held beliefs and discover truth. In reality though, people are ostracized for speaking the truth before it is a widely known or held belief (e.g Mandela). This leads to mob justice, if the incumbent believers will suffer from the truth.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: Examples to ponder : Geocentricity, Flat Earth, Racism, Slavery, Dictatorships, Alchemy, etc. As a species, we are able to discover the truth over centuries through the passage of time and the ability to pass on knowledge from one generation to the next.

name: Vinny Lingham
tweet: Truth is often just a function of time. Humans tend to have a short term view of the truth and therefore the perception of what is true or false cannot be deduced within our lifetimes or fragments of time within them.
